### ZFS Pool Creation

> If your nodes have a single NVMe, set `proxmox.storage_pool: local-zfs` in
> `site/config.yaml` and skip this step. The Proxmox installer already created
> the storage.

Create the ZFS data pool on each node's data NVMe drive:

```bash
framework/scripts/configure-node-storage.sh --all
```

Or configure a single node:
```bash
framework/scripts/configure-node-storage.sh <node-name>
```

Preview what will be done without making changes:
```bash
framework/scripts/configure-node-storage.sh --dry-run --all
```

The script identifies the data NVMe automatically (the unpartitioned drive
that is not the boot disk) and creates a ZFS pool named `{{ storage.pool_name }}`.

If the script cannot identify the data drive (e.g., both NVMe drives have
partitions, or there are more than two NVMe devices), it will report an error.
In that case, identify the drive manually with `lsblk` and pass it explicitly:
```bash
framework/scripts/configure-node-storage.sh <node-name> --device /dev/nvme1n1
```

**Verification:**
{% for node in nodes %}
- [ ] {{ node.name }}: `ssh root@{{ node.mgmt_ip }} zpool status {{ storage.pool_name }}`
      → ONLINE, no errors
{% endfor %}

