After all nodes are installed and reachable on the management network, run:

```bash
framework/scripts/configure-node-network.sh --all
```

Use `--all` for initial setup. Single-node mode is useful when re-deploying
after a config change or when recovering a single node:
```bash
framework/scripts/configure-node-network.sh <node-name>
```

Preview what will be deployed without making changes:
```bash
framework/scripts/configure-node-network.sh --dry-run <node-name>
```

The script will generate and deploy `/etc/network/interfaces` on each node,
configure `/etc/hosts`, `/etc/resolv.conf`, and `/etc/issue`, then verify
connectivity.

> **Note:** The script configures `vmbr0` as a VLAN-aware bridge and adds
> `bridge-vlans` entries for each VLAN ID defined in `config.yaml → environments`.
> This is required — a VLAN-aware bridge without explicit VLAN IDs will not
> forward tagged frames. If VMs show zero rx-bytes after deployment, verify
> that `/etc/network/interfaces` on the node includes the correct `bridge-vlans`
> directive (e.g., `bridge-vlans 2-4094` or the specific VLAN IDs).

Here is what it will configure:

| Node | Interface | Role | IP |
|------|-----------|------|----|
{%- for node in nodes %}
| {{ node.name }} | {{ node.mgmt_iface }} (vmbr0) | Management | {{ node.mgmt_ip }}/{{ management.subnet | cidr_prefix }} |
{%- if node.repl_ip is defined and node.repl_ip %}
| {{ node.name }} | dummy0 | Corosync ring0 | {{ node.repl_ip }}/32 |
{%- endif %}
{%- if node.repl_peers is defined and node.repl_peers %}
{%- for peer_name, peer in node.repl_peers.items() %}
| {{ node.name }} | {{ peer.iface }} | Replication → {{ peer_name }} | {{ peer.local_ip }} |
{%- endfor %}
{%- endif %}
{%- endfor %}
{%- if has_replication_network %}

> **How replication network failover works:** Each node has two static routes
> to each peer's corosync address — a direct route (low metric) and a fallback
> route (high metric) through the third node. If a DAC cable fails, the kernel
> detects carrier loss, removes the direct route, and traffic automatically
> reroutes through the surviving node. All nodes have IP forwarding enabled
> to support this relay behavior.
{%- endif %}

